EXP NO :20

Aim :
To implement the use of binary operator overloading using object-oriented programming in C++.

Algorithm :
Start the program.
Define a class (e.g., Number) with private data members.
Create a constructor to initialize the data members.
Declare and define a function to overload a binary operator (like +, -, *, or /).
This function will take one argument (the right-hand operand).
The left-hand operand is the calling object.
Perform the required operation inside the overloaded operator function.
Return the result as an object.
In main(), create two objects and use the overloaded operator between them.
Display the result.
End the program.

Program :
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Number {
private:
    int a;

public:
    // Constructor
    Number(int x = 0) {
        a = x;
    }

    // Overloading binary + operator
    Number operator+(Number obj) {
        Number temp;
        temp.a = a + obj.a;  // 'a' of left object + 'a' of right object
        return temp;
    }

    // Display function
    void display() {
        cout << "Value: " << a << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Number n1(10), n2(20), n3;

    cout << "First number: ";
    n1.display();

    cout << "Second number: ";
    n2.display();

    n3 = n1 + n2;  // Using overloaded + operator

    cout << "After adding objects: ";
    n3.display();

    return 0;
}

Output :
First number: Value: 10
Second number: Value: 20
After adding objects: Value: 30

Result :
Binary operator (+) overloading is successfully implemented using OOP in C++.
